        "seoKeywords": "Spencer Strider,Atlanta Braves",
        "body": "\u003Cp\u003EATLANTA -- \u003Cforge-entity title=\"Spencer Strider\" slug=\"spencer-strider-675911\" code=\"player\"\u003ESpencer Strider\u003C/forge-entity\u003E and \u003Cforge-entity title=\"Ronald Acu&#241;a Jr.\" slug=\"ronald-acuna-jr-660670\" code=\"player\"\u003ERonald Acu&#241;a Jr.\u003C/forge-entity\u003E had the Braves playing like it was 2023 again.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStrider displayed his dominant form for the first time since returning from last year’s season-ending right elbow surgery and Acuña homered for the seventh time since returning three weeks ago after his own year-long absence. Their contributions helped the Braves as they beat the Rockies, \u003Ca href=\"https://www.mlb.com/gameday/rockies-vs-braves/2025/06/14/777523/final/box\" target=\"_blank\"\u003E4-1\u003C/a\u003E, Saturday afternoon at Truist Park to capture their third straight win.\n\nAcuña’s two-run homer in the second inning created an early cushion for Strider, who recorded 13 strikeouts over six scoreless innings. This was his 18th double-digit-strikeout game during a career that has consisted of just 60 starts. But it was his first since Sept. 19, 2023. Rafael Montero and Dylan Lee combined for six strikeouts over the final three frames to give the Braves a franchise-record 19 K's for the game.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Ciframe class=\"story-player-iframe\" sandbox=\"allow-top-navigation-by-user-activation allow-popups-to-escape-sandbox allow-forms allow-modals allow-pointer-lock allow-popups allow-same-origin allow-scripts allow-top-navigation\"  style=\"width: 100%; border: 0px; height: 400px;\" src=\"https://www.mlb.com/stories/game/777523\"\u003E\u003C/iframe\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Braves and Strider have patiently waited for him to distance himself enough from surgery to have an outing like this. The 26-year-old hurler struck out 13 of the 22 batters he faced with a fastball that averaged a season-high 96.2 mph. This pitch had averaged just 95.1 mph in his previous five starts this year. The Rockies also had no chance against Strider’s slider, whiffing with 17 of 23 swings against that pitch.\n\nStrider was a preseason Cy Young Award favorite after tallying a franchise-record 281 strikeouts in 2023. But he underwent season-ending elbow surgery after his second start of the 2024 season, and he has spent the past couple months battling to prove he could still be a top-flight starter.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStrider returned from elbow surgery on April 16, strained his right hamstring five days later and spent another month on the injured list. He entered Saturday having posted a 5.85 ERA over the four starts he had made since returning from the injured list the second time.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAcuña missed last year’s final four months after suffering an anterior cruciate ligament tear for the second time in four seasons. But the 2023 National League MVP hasn’t had much trouble proving he remains one of the game’s elite players. He has hit .387 with a 1.178 OPS since returning.\u003C/p\u003E",
        "contributors": [
          {
            "name": "Mark Bowman"
          }
        ],
